Defines the tree data model consumed by `viz/index.html` to render the stroke browser: `Category` (root-level groupings in file order) and `Tree` (all nodes keyed by identity, in first-seen order for deterministic output). `build.rs` populates a `Tree`; `axis.rs` defines the `Axis` type used for synthetic choice nodes.

The key insight is that node identity isn't 1:1 with authored lines: `@count`/`@fuse` alternatives collapse into a single "axis" choice node (see `axis.rs`), and a stroke's one-liner (`U`) variant merges into the same node as its multi-line sibling via `group_key`. `group_key` strips the injected `U` marker from the first `/`-segment's key set and *re-renders* it (not string-splices) because hyphen placement in stroke notation depends on which keys are present — splicing would produce invalid/mismatched stroke text.

`Node` carries both `multi_line` and `one_liner` preview text options plus `one_liner_root` (the `U`-augmented first segment of the one-liner variant, i.e. the physical stroke that actually differs — cross-reference `lineflag.rs` for what this is used for downstream). `synthetic: bool` marks `##>` section-grouping nodes that have no real authored stroke; the viewer skips drawing a keyboard diagram for these.

`position(key, category_label, section)` computes a leaf's parent-bucketing key: root strokes get a synthetic `cat:{label}` position, section-tagged descendants get a synthetic `sec:{parent} {label}` position (built by `section_position`), others just use the stroke's `/`-parent prefix. `section_parts(key)` is the inverse parser, splitting on the first space — this only works because `section_position`'s `parent` is guaranteed space-free (it's `/`-joined stroke text). The `SEC_PREFIX = "sec:"` constant and the single-space delimiter convention must stay in sync between `section_position` and `section_parts`.

`group_key` and `strip_u` are infallible in practice despite returning `Result` — they can only fail if `parse_stroke` rejects a `U`-injected segment that other code (`add_key`) itself produced, which shouldn't happen.